UML:TaggedValue.value: This actor supports the principal investigator in performing data entry tasks such as submitting a project's experimental design, sample annotation and quality control metrics used in the collection and treatment of the samples. While the project's "owner" is the Principal Investigator, we anticipate that the data entry activities will be performed by individuals with this role assigned

caArray User is anyone who directly accesses caArray, via the interactive or programmatic interfaces.
Immediate descendents include Registered User and Anonymous User.
In the case of extraction, a caArray User has a need to extract arrays (including array data and annotaitons) for "downstream" use, such as analysis via analytic tools or importing into additional repositories.

A system administrator is responsible for ensuring caArray operates effectively. They are repsonsible for managing users and groups, providing status of the quality of operation of the caArray application, and ensuring the system is backed up and recoverable, among other things.
A lab administrator is responsible for managing lab operations. They will typically interact with submitting investigators, assign work, and run reports on the operations of the lab.

A project submitter is a specific form of Registered User who will be most likely to make submissions of projects, including the experimental design, the desired samples and the quality control governing the samples. They will belong to an institution, most likely through an association with a particular research lab.

A collaborator is assigned by a Principal Investigator to receive a "preview" of a project and possibly even work on a subset of the project. A preview represents access to a project prior to its being made public by the Principal Investigator. The collaborator(s) is expected to actively contribute to the project's execution by providing samples and/or analysis.
NOTE: We do not believe Patient will be in scope for 2.0, but we felt we should capture it for now.
A specific form of Submitter, a Principal Investigator (PI) typically owns experiments and studies/projects.

LDAP (Lightweight Directory Access Protocol) is a software protocol for enabling anyone to locate organizations, individuals, and other resources such as files and devices in a network, whether on the public Internet or on a corporate intranet. LDAP is a "lightweight" (smaller amount of code) version of Directory Access Protocol (DAP), which is part of X.500, a standard for directory services in a network. LDAP is lighter because in its initial version it did not include security features. LDAP originated at the University of Michigan and has been endorsed by at least 40 companies.
Patients are not currently believed to be in scope. We will color Patient in the future to make clearly show their "future-ness."
A generalization of the core facility roles, this actor is used to simplify use case writing.

A curator is a caArray user responsible for curating the data present in caArray. Curators have special privileges to ensure the quality (through editing, demoting, and promoting) the content of caArray.
Submit New Ontological Entries to EVS
This is any user who visits caArray but does not get identified through a log in or other form of authentication/authorization. Another name for this actor might be "public user."
Submit New Ontological Entries to EVS

A biostatistician is a special form of submitter who is responsible for statistical analysis of project data. The key actions to be performed are review of experiment designs, submission of quality control metadata, and uploading of normalized data and the annotation of the parameters used.

A generalized Actor intended to represent those applications/systems that programmatically communicate with caArray. Examples of external sstems we know want to interact with caArray include WebGenome, geWorkBench, and caIntegrator. Examples of programmatic access might include an API, web service, or grid -- specific mechanisms that will be supported have not been solidified.

A registered user is a specific form of caArray User who is known to caArray (done so throuhg the act of registering).
One must be a Registered User before one can submit to caArray.
In terms of submission, a registered user can actively contrbute and maintain arrays (including array annotations and array data) to caArray. Registered users who perform submissions are typically researchers with something valuable to offer caArray, such as a Lab Scientist or Prinicpal Investigator.
A lab scientist is the primary handler of samples in the lab. They run the experiments, collaborate with the statisticians and document their activities step by step.
A data owner represents the primary users of the application from the research lab and the core facility.
This set of use cases describes the actions and benefits of executing the workflow between the lab and the PIs and within the lab team members

Initiated by any caArray User, this use case allows for the extraction of data from any publicly available instance of caArray. No permission restrictions are required to acquire the data, either at a project level or inidvidual samples within or across projects. For data that is permission protected, the same mechanism will apply but only users associated with the project will be able to perform this action. Once the data of interest is found, the user should be informed of expected download time.

Initiated by an External System - though primarily by caBIG Analysis Services - this use case allows for the extraction of project data that is public and protected data is the appropriate authorization is used. This is not intended to be executed through a user interface, rather this will be accomplished through an API and will likely invoke other use cases (particularly search) to find and then acquire the data desired to be pulled into the other application. The use case may expand to include external systems such as GEO or Array Express or other systems that are local to the installer that may have an interest in the data contained in caArray.

Initiated by any user, this use case allows for a subset of array data and its associated annotation to be extracted from caArray. Rather than pulling the entire .cel file for example, a much smaller subset of the data contained within the .cel file would be available - such as five of the thousands of rows for a given set of gene names.
This set of use cases describes the actions and benefits of executing the workflow between the lab and the PIs and within the lab team members
All required fields must be validated prior to submission. Only valid studies can be submitted.
The study can be saved at any point for the purpose of saving progress. Validation restrictions are waived.

Initiated by a Lab Administrator, this use case provides the ability to review a project submitted to the administrators core, edit it if necessary, write comments and make a decision to return it for revision, reject it or approve the project.

Initiated by a Principal Investigator, this use case allows for the creation, editing and submission of annotation supporting array projects. Several high level items will be covered including the platform of choice, funding mechanism, and sample annotation. A minimum set of information must be collected prior to being allowed to submit but almost as soon as a project is begun it can be saved as draft to be retrieved by the Principal Investigator when desired. In addition, the PI may choose to have a research scientist complete the submission on their behalf.

Initiated by a Data Owner, this use case allows for the promotion of a project's visibility. This action can apply to an entire project or to specific samples within the project. The basic visibility states of the project are: restricted, institution, group, public and collaborator. There is no restriction on changing a project's visibility, though it is not advisable once a publication has been published against the project.
Initiated by a Lab Administrator, this use case supports the assignment of a lab scientist and a biostatistician for a particular project or reassigns the project as needed.

Initiated by the Principal Investigator, this use case allows for editing a proposed project to reflect changes requested by the lab administrator or to simply update a proposal that is in draft status.

Initiated by the Lab Scientist and at key analytical and quality control points, the Biostatistician, this use case allows them to detail what work they are doing step by step. The data entry performed will also be used by the system to inform the Principal Investigator and others interested, to see the status of work and kick-off timers for additional use cases.

Initiated by a Data Owner, this use case allows for a per project or per form validation to be run and to return positive or negative reports to the user. In the case of a negative report, the area of MIAME affected and the causal elements (or lack thereof) will be presented. The report status does not affect whether the project can continue or even to be made public. However, indicators will be present in a summary view of the project and it can be used as a search criteria.
Initiated by a caArray user, this use case allows for anyone to view whether a project in MIAME compliance or not and to investigate why it isnt.

Initiated by a Data Owner, this use case allows for the creation, editing and deletion of publication associations to a project. Common formats for publications will be presented in addition to the ability to auto-populate the fields based on pubmed id. Several types of publications are available: manuscripts, abstracts and posters. More than one association can be made.

Initiated by a Curator, this use case allows for the import of non-project specific entries into caArray. Specifically, the entries include: contacts and organizations, protocols, hardware and software. For people, this use case does not create accounts - it just lessons the effort required to do so. The format for the import is to be determined but MAGE-TAB is an expected candidate.

Initiated by a Curator, this use case allows for the uploading of array designs on an as needed basis. A significant number of array designs will come pre-loaded from the NCICB but when necessary, a particular institution may need to upload array designs that are dated (when pushing in legacy data) or be in front of the curve (prior to official support).

Initiated by a Data Owner, this use case allows for the validation of file structure and content for annotation or array data, with a future intent to import the data into the project. The content validation is not to determine the accuracy of the information from a scientific viewpoint; rather it is purely to ensure that the data files loaded are sound for importing into the system. This use case will also be invoked when a Data Owner chooses to import non-validated data.
Initiated by a Data Owner, this use case enables the import of annotation and array data from previously-uploaded files.

Initiated by a Data Owner, this use case enables the uploading of annotation and array content collectively and independently into a caArray project and then provides the ability to validate, import and/or delete the uploaded files and records each action taken. Due to the large file size of array data and to a lesser extent the annotation, the upload may take minutes or even hours to complete; so the ability to offer to run the upload in the background (allowing the user to perform other functions inside caArray) is desirable.

Initiated by any Data Owner for a particular Institute, this use case enables the project annotation and array data to be deposited in web-based microarray repositories. Two repositories have been identified, the Gene Expression Omnibus and Array Express. The desire is to enable the system to automate this process fully, but a manual process will be required until those two systems allow for other techniques to be employed. Once a project has been submitted, the status will be indicated to all. Special Requirements, such as acquiring and inputting the Accession Number from GEO on a per sample basis will become available.

This is a conventional field-based search. The filters for each entity that can be searched are driven by those entities. For example, Name or Applicable Platform might be filters for a search of and for Array Designs.

This use case permits Registered Users to preserve references to arrays for ease of access and navigation in future sessions. the concepts of folders and subfolders will likely be very familiar to users and we intend to put as few limitations/structure as possible. A default structure of projects and samples will be made available. This is distinct from virtual projects which collects references within one project.

Initiated by a caArray User, this use case presents a tabular, and perhaps graphical, representation of high level meta data about the contents of the repository. The number of projects available by state, species, platform and disease type will be displayed with the ability to switch from a local instance to those available across the caGRID.

UML:UseCase.name: Search for Arrays Using Natural Text

UML:TaggedValue.value:
A.K.A. "Spotlight" Search or "Horizontal" Search
This is a free text, single edit field search that quickly finds results (<10 seconds typically) though the results will be governed (e..g, never more than 150 arrays returned). It is assumed a handful of important (and indexed) fields are considered. Consider the Spotlight search Apple employes, particulalry the text search of the Apple iTunes Store.... millions of items to be searched, extremely fast and governeed results.
Search for Arrays Using Natural Text

This is a generlized use case that describes how users will be able to locate content of caArray based on user-specified criteria. We will likely offer several forms, including friendly "iTunes-like" natural text searches that search a limited set of often-referenced values, filter-based searches on high level entities (protocols, investigator, etc.), and potentially more discrete/field-specific searches based on specific values and ranges of values (such as certain genes with a minimal intensity value, or specific probe sets, etc.). The most significant value will be not just the ability to find information but to do something with the result - download the data, directly hyperlink to additional data, easily refine the query parameters.

Initiated by any Registered User, this use case enables the creation, editing, and deletion of virtual projects within one's workspace. A virtual project contains references to other project information, most commonly sample annotation and arrays, and supports features common to "real" projects, such as downloading data. The names must be unique per user and will be made available when reviewing other projects for taking additive actions (e.g., "send to virtual project").

Initiated by any Registered User, this use case allows for the saving of criteria used in searches that the user found valuable. They will be able to name the search, re-run it when they like, and change paramters. While no version control is expected (or implied) the abilty to copy a search and modiy the copy is available to the user. In addition, the ability to share a "query definition"(the name plus the parameters) with another user is envisioned though defered past 2.0

The act of curation must not be overlooked. Several alternatives to caArray have found that they invest a significant amount of resources as curators.
The sorts of things we anticipate requiring curation include:
1) Shareable resources such as protocols and array designs and their names.
2) Experiments, to ensure that their annotaitons are meaningful and consistent.
3) Proposal and promotion of ontology entries, even those that are merely referenced by caArray but are maintained by external organizations.

Mervi specifically asked that we ensure reporting is well represented, but we have not yet received any specific requirements related to reporting.
We believe that a lot of the caArray user community would currently consider a "report" is going to be provided as conventional view information in caArray 2. For example, we have discussed "Dashboard" views to provide overview information regarding the state of the repository.

Initiated by a Curator, this use case allows for the review of entries made by Data Owners in the execution of a project. Similar to the spirit of copy editing a paper, the meaning can't be changed, only clarified or made consistent, in support of quality project annotation.

Initiated by the Curator, Curate is a generalized use case to describe the act of curating caArray's submitted content.
The sorts of things we anticipate requiring curation include:
1) Shareable resources such as protocols and array designs and their names.
2) Projects, to ensure that their annotaitons are meaningful and consistent.
3) Proposal and promotion of ontology entries, even those that are merely referenced by caArray but are maintained by external organizations.

Initiated by a Curator, this use case reports on new terms that have been submitted by Data Owners during the course of a project's execution. The data is made available as soon as a project has moved into the "complete' state. The report allows a curator to review any new items and to take the appropriate action (accept or edit).

UML:TaggedValue.value: Initiated by a Curator, this use case allows for the compilation of entries that have resulted from project activity or which are invented by the Curator and submit them to EVS.

We believe that a lot of the caArray user community would currently consider a "report" is going to be provided as conventional view information in caArray 2. For example, we have discussed "Dashboard" views to provide overview information regarding the state of the repository which is currently represented in the Search and Navigation package.
External Stakeholders indicated that items such as project reporting are "nice to have" but not even of low priority.

Initiated by any Registered User, this use case allows for the validation of the authenticity and authority of the given user either against a networked (LDAP) set of users or a local set (database). As a result of a successful login, the registered user is presented with their home space and the set of operations they have been granted privileges to perform.

Activate a User: An Admin user can disable an "Inactive" caArray user from the Modify User Details screen. On this screen, there will be a button Activate User next to the user status. Clicking on this button will attempt to set the End Date value a blank string (null value). On successful save of the user information, the user account will be seen as active since there is no end date specified.
Search: An admin user can search for groups existing in the system. The "Group Name" can be used as criteria to narrow down the groups list.
An Admin user can disable an "Active" caArray user from the Modify User Details screen. On this screen, there will be a button Disable User next to the user status. Clicking on this button will attempt to set the End Date value to the previous days date. On successful save of the user information, the user account will be deemed to be inactive as the end date is set to the previous day.
Once the Admin User accesses the User Management Area of the application, they can search for other caArray users. The following fields have been identified (initially) that can be used as criteria to narrow down the user list: + Login Name + First Name + Last Name + Institution + E-Mail Address
Once a user has been found, the logged-in Admin user can view the user details by clicking on the hyperlinked User Name or Login Name fields.

Initiated by a System Administrator, this use case allows for the creation, editing and deletion of an Institution's groups. This typically will help organize an institution's research labs and core facilities, which will allows for organizing users among them. However, the ability to create supersets of institutions will also be available to the System Administrator.

Initiated by a registered user, this use case allows for the creation, editing and deletion of collaboration groups and the users within them. This set of users can then be given access by a Data Owner to a project, set of projects or particular samples and their underlying array data. In order to add a collaborator, they must also be registered in the system.

Initiated by an Anonymous User, this use case allows the user to gain access to restricted features. This may occassionally be performed on behalf of an anonymous user by the System Administrator.
This functionality will allow the Admin user(s) to create new users for the caArray application. Note that the Password and Confirm Password fields are displayed only when the database is being used for authentication. If LDAP authentication is in use, these fields are not displayed and are, hence, not required.

Only Admin users will be allowed access to the User Management area. On successful login, the application will determine "User Management" tab will be visible on the caArray home page before the "Logout" tab. Clicking on the User Management tab will redirect the logged in user to the User Management Area/Section of the application.
If the logged in user is not an Admin, then the tab will not be displayed. Any attempts to navigate directly to that URL will display a page that specifies the logged-in user does not have sufficient privileges (or appropriate role) to perform this operation, with instructions on whom to contact to rectify the situation.
Any changes to the user privileges (ability to view/not view the User Management area) will take effect when the caArray user logs into the application the next time.
